WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
[Music]

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:11.960
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today&nbsp;
we're going to start to establish proper,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:17.240
solid foundations for algebra. I've&nbsp;
already given quite a few talks in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:24.040
this series on algebra, but up till now,&nbsp;
it's all been rather informal, loose,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:31.400
and vague, just like it's usually taught in&nbsp;
schools and universities. Such an approach,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:38.600
even though it may be useful and&nbsp;
popular, is nevertheless weak logically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:44.760
and we need to move up a step or several steps&nbsp;
and address the issue of what exactly are the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:52.240
fundamental objects. The fundamental objects&nbsp;
in algebra are closely related to polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:59.920
and we can focus our attention, to begin with,&nbsp;
on this question of what exactly is a polynomial.

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:06.000
Well, we've seen several subtly different ways&nbsp;
in which this notion has manifested itself so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.640
far. We've talked about arithmetical&nbsp;
expressions involving unknown numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:21.080
for example, 3 + 2x^2 - x^3, where x represents&nbsp;
an unknown number. We can think about formulas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:28.960
involving a general number n, for example, our&nbsp;
formula for the nth triangular number. Sometimes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:36.560
a polynomial is considered as a function with a&nbsp;
graph, something like this. Or we can think of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:43.600
polynomial occasionally in terms of a constituent&nbsp;
of an identity. For example, here's a variant on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:49.240
the geometric series identity. It's a very nice&nbsp;
identity, and we can think, well, this is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:56.480
polynomial here, this is a polynomial here, there&nbsp;
are polynomials involved in identities like this.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:01.040
So there are a number of different&nbsp;
possible ways of approaching polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:07.160
but it's absolutely necessary to decide on&nbsp;
one and to specify and clarify completely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:12.440
what exactly this is. Most algebra&nbsp;
texts fall short when it comes to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:19.240
this important task. But if we do not specify&nbsp;
very clearly what the fundamental objects are,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:23.240
the entire theory that we build is&nbsp;
logically weak and ultimately doesn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:29.480
really make mathematical sense, even though&nbsp;
it may give us a warm and fuzzy feeling.

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:35.240
So let us turn now to the question: how are&nbsp;
we going to think about what a polynomial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:42.360
is? My approach is rather unorthodox&nbsp;
here. I believe that polynomials are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:48.560
properly built on a foundation of&nbsp;
other objects called poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:53.960
and I'm going to tell you what poly numbers&nbsp;
are and how to do arithmetic with them. Once&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.960 --> 00:03:00.000
we understand that, then what a polynomial&nbsp;
is will become very simple and elegant.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:07.600
So let's turn to the issue: what is a poly&nbsp;
number? Let me remind you that so far in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:15.160
our framework for arithmetic, we've talked&nbsp;
about natural numbers, integers, fractions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:22.000
and culminating in the rational number&nbsp;
field. Our basic operations are addition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:29.240
multiplication, subtraction, and division. We're&nbsp;
going to mimic what goes on here in a higher or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:35.480
more sophisticated context. We're going to&nbsp;
introduce things called poly numbers or,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:41.200
more particularly, positive poly numbers.&nbsp;
We're going to introduce integral poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:47.200
fractional poly numbers, and then ultimately&nbsp;
rational poly numbers. It will turn out that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:52.640
rational poly numbers are also a field, just&nbsp;
in the same way that the rational numbers are a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:59.080
field. Furthermore, these two fields—the field&nbsp;
of rational numbers and the field of rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:08.200
poly numbers—are the two most important fields&nbsp;
in mathematics. That's number one and that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:15.640
number two. So this is a very important setup that&nbsp;
we're doing here. We have to understand these poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:20.520
numbers, and we're going to proceed in a way which&nbsp;
is very analogous to how we proceeded with setting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.520 --> 00:04:29.120
up arithmetic in the first place. We're going to&nbsp;
start with the poly equivalent of natural numbers.

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:35.000
Let's go back to the very first videos in this&nbsp;
series on mathematics foundations where we were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.600
talking about arithmetic, and I hope you recall&nbsp;
that we started off with the natural numbers:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:50.640
1, 2, 3, and so on. We introduced a type for&nbsp;
those natural numbers. We said num will be the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:57.560
name of that type of mathematical object. Then a&nbsp;
little while later, we established the integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.560 --> 00:05:04.360
which include not just the natural numbers&nbsp;
but also 0, -1, -2, and so on. That was its&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:10.960
type. Now it's useful for us to introduce&nbsp;
a slight variant on the natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:18.480
and we'll call these the positive numbers. The&nbsp;
only difference will be that we'll include zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:26.880
So a positive number is, by definition,&nbsp;
a natural number or zero. We'll call that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:34.720
new type num plus. It's just a little bit more&nbsp;
than the natural numbers; we've thrown in zero.

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:39.680
When I started this video, I had to decide whether&nbsp;
I was going to start with this as the basic object&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.680 --> 00:05:45.200
or this as the basic object, and there were good&nbsp;
reasons to do either of them. In computer science,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:52.960
it's often useful to start counting with zero, but&nbsp;
I felt that historically and perhaps intuitively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:59.680
it was more natural to start with one. However,&nbsp;
it's clear that zero together with the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:07.720
numbers is also an important mathematical object,&nbsp;
and so now we have a name for it and a new type.

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:14.440
Alright, so now let's define what a positive&nbsp;
poly number is. This is a fundamental definition:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:20.840
a positive poly number is a list of&nbsp;
positive numbers written vertically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:27.120
with a bracket on top. So there's P;&nbsp;
that's a positive poly number. n0, n1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:34.320
n2 down to some nk—these are all positive numbers&nbsp;
in the sense that we've just defined here. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:41.520
they're all either zeros or natural numbers,&nbsp;
and there's a bracket on top of this list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:47.880
alerting us to the fact that this object&nbsp;
is a new kind of object called a positive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:56.040
poly number. These are going to be the&nbsp;
building blocks for this new arithmetic.

00:06:56.040 --> 00:07:06.680
So for example, here is a positive poly number:&nbsp;
it's (1,3) with a bracket on top. Here is Q,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:14.880
which is (2,2,1,4). Here is R, which is just&nbsp;
(1,7) with a bracket on top of it. Here is T,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:19.280
which is (0,3,0) with a bracket on top of it.

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:25.040
Now there's an important notion of equality&nbsp;
between two positive poly numbers. We say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:32.880
that P and P'—two positive poly numbers—are&nbsp;
equal precisely when one can be obtained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:40.960
from the other by adding or removing&nbsp;
zeros from the bottom. So for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:47.800
this positive poly number and this positive poly&nbsp;
number are equal because this one's obtained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:53.360
from this one by adding a zero on the bottom or&nbsp;
conversely this one's obtained from this one by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:59.400
removing a zero from the bottom. Here in this&nbsp;
example, here are two positive poly numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.400 --> 00:08:05.120
which are not equal: we've removed a zero,&nbsp;
but we haven't removed it from the bottom,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.120 --> 00:08:10.480
so that's no good. You're not allowed&nbsp;
to do that. This is not equal to this.

00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:16.280
There are two basic operations on positive&nbsp;
poly numbers, just as there are on natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:24.240
numbers. These operations are addition&nbsp;
and multiplication. Addition is very easy;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:32.320
multiplication is less easy. Let me illustrate&nbsp;
these by giving you a challenge. I'm going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:36.440
just illustrate what the two operations&nbsp;
do in some examples. I'm going to ask&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:40.720
you to go away and figure out what&nbsp;
the operations are by studying these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.720 --> 00:08:45.320
examples. I'm only going to give you one&nbsp;
example for addition because it's so easy.

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:50.560
So here's an example of the addition&nbsp;
of this poly number with this poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.560 --> 00:08:54.680
number: (1,2,3) + (2,3,1) = (3,5,4). I've&nbsp;
given you three examples of multiplication:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.680 --> 00:09:02.720
(1,2) * (2,1) = (2,5,2); (1,1,1) * (1,1,1) =&nbsp;
(1,2,3,2,1); (2,0,1) * (1,1) = (2,2,1). I want you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:07.240
to study these three examples. If it's not obvious&nbsp;
to you already—I know for some of you it will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:14.400
completely clear—but if it's not, make sure you&nbsp;
understand or try to unravel what the rule is.

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:19.160
Next time, I'm going to very clearly&nbsp;
lay out what these two operations are,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:23.960
and we're going to start doing arithmetic&nbsp;
with poly numbers. But multiplication is so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:31.240
important that it's useful for you to think about&nbsp;
it beforehand to try to get some feeling for it.

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:35.360
So next time, it's arithmetic&nbsp;
with positive poly numbers. I hope&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:46.280
you'll join me for that. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:47.280
[Music]

